#compdef obelisk
# ============================================================================
# obelisk - save a web page as a single self-contained
#            HTML file (Go, MIT)
#
# Author : Radhi Fadlillah (go-shiori)
# Upstream: https://github.com/go-shiori/obelisk
#
# `obelisk` walks a URL's rendered HTML tree,
# downloads every referenced resource (images, CSS,
# fonts, scripts, embedded media), inlines all of
# them into a single output HTML file using
# data: URIs + embedded `<style>` blocks, and emits
# the resulting fully-self-contained document. The
# output works offline + can be archived to disk +
# shared as a single artifact.
#
# Use cases:
#   - Personal archive of web articles for offline
#     reading
#   - Citation-stable HTML snapshots for academic
#     work
#   - "Save Page As → Single File" automation
#     (browser extension `SingleFile` is the same
#     concept but inside a browser; obelisk is the
#     command-line equivalent)
#   - Time-Capsule-style website archival
#
# Part of the go-shiori suite (alongside `shiori`
# the self-hosted bookmark manager + `dom` Go DOM
# library + the broader go-shiori bookmarking
# ecosystem).
#
# Usage:
#   obelisk <url1> [<url2> ...] [flags]
#   obelisk -i urls.txt -o archive/ [flags]
#
# Args:
#   <urlN>                   - URLs to archive
#                              (variadic)
#
# Input flags:
#   -i, --input <file>       - file containing URLs
#                              (one per line)
#   -c, --load-cookies <file>
#                            - Netscape-format cookie
#                              file for authenticated
#                              fetches
#
# Output flags:
#   -o, --output <path>      - output file or
#                              directory (default
#                              current dir; use "-"
#                              for stdout)
#   -z, --gzip               - gzip-compress the
#                              archival result
#
# Content filtering:
#       --no-js              - strip JavaScript
#       --no-css             - strip CSS styling
#       --no-embeds          - strip embedded
#                              elements (iframes,
#                              etc.)
#       --no-medias          - strip media elements
#                              (img, audio, video)
#
# Logging:
#   -q, --quiet              - disable all logging
#       --verbose            - verbose logging
#
# Network:
#   -u, --user-agent <ua>    - custom User-Agent
#                              header
#   -r, --retries <N>        - max retries per
#                              request (default 3)
#   -t, --timeout <secs>     - per-request timeout
#                              (default 60)
#       --insecure           - skip TLS certificate
#                              verification
#       --max-concurrent-download <N>
#                            - concurrent download
#                              cap (default 10)
#       --skip-resource-url-error
#                            - continue on resource
#                              fetch errors instead
#                              of aborting
#
# Global:
#   -h, --help               - print help
#
# The tdewolff/parse/css lane is built on `github.
# com/tdewolff/parse/v2 v2.7.11` (declared verbatim
# at upstream go.mod HEAD as a direct dep, used in
# process-css.go to rewrite CSS `url()` references
# to inlined data: URIs before embedding the stylesheet
# in the output HTML), the canonical Go CSS parser
# by Taco de Wolff (tdewolff) - github.com/tdewolff/
# parse, 1300+ stars on the multi-format umbrella.
#
# tdewolff/parse is a *multi-format parsing
# umbrella* covering:
#   - CSS (Selectors L4 + Syntax L3 + the core CSS
#     modules)
#   - HTML (WHATWG HTML5 tokenizer + tree builder)
#   - JavaScript (ECMAScript 2022 grammar)
#   - JSON (RFC 8259)
#   - XML (XML 1.0 5th edition)
#   - SVG (SVG 1.1 + 2.0)
#
# All six format-parser modules sit under one
# umbrella crate, sharing a common
# `parse.Input` / `parse.Output` IO abstraction +
# the same memory-efficient streaming-token approach.
# This is a structurally different approach from the
# Rust slot (parcel-bundler/lightningcss, specialized
# CSS-only library) and the Node slot (postcss,
# CSS-only ecosystem with thousands of plugins).
#
# de Wolff's umbrella also publishes `tdewolff/
# minify` - a multi-format minifier built ON TOP of
# the parsers. The two umbrellas (parse + minify)
# pair naturally: parse extracts the AST, minify
# transforms the AST + serializes the minimal
# representation back out.
#
# Production users of tdewolff/parse + minify:
#   - Caddy (HTML/CSS/JS response-body minification
#     middleware)
#   - Hugo (SSG asset minification pipeline)
#   - Vugu (Go-WASM web framework's asset compiler)
#   - obelisk (THIS BINARY)
#   - many of the Go static-site generators in the
#     broader ecosystem
#
# obelisk uses `parse/css` specifically in `process-
# css.go` to identify all `url(...)` references in
# downloaded stylesheets, then fetch + inline each
# referenced resource as a data: URI before the
# stylesheet gets embedded in the output HTML's
# `<style>` block.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 258 :: CSS parser libraries (CSS Syntax L3 +
#              Selectors L4 + ~30 other CSS specs)
# Round 1473 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 258
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : parcel-bundler/lightningcss  [R1472 _stencila]
#   Go      : tdewolff/parse/css           [R1473 THIS FILE]
#   TS/Node : postcss                      [R1474 closing]
#
# tdewolff/parse/css is structurally interesting
# because of its *multi-format-parsing-umbrella*
# pattern. The three lanes form a clean spectrum
# of CSS-parsing-library scope:
#
#   - Rust (lightningcss): CSS-specialized library
#     with transforms + browser-targeting + minify
#     baked in; written specifically for Parcel 2's
#     pipeline; lightningcss-only repo
#   - Go (tdewolff/parse/css): CSS module inside a
#     6-format parsing umbrella (HTML + CSS + JS +
#     JSON + XML + SVG); shared IO + streaming-token
#     abstraction across all formats
#   - Node (postcss): CSS-specialized ecosystem with
#     thousands of plugins (Autoprefixer + cssnano +
#     Tailwind + Stylelint + cssnext); not just a
#     parser but a full transformation pipeline
#
# Each lane reflects its host ecosystem's library
# culture:
#   - Rust's "purpose-built single-library
#     replacement" pattern (lightningcss replaces
#     PostCSS for Parcel)
#   - Go's "shared utility umbrella" pattern (parse +
#     minify pair across 6 formats)
#   - Node's "plugin ecosystem" pattern (postcss as
#     a platform with 3rd-party transforms)
#
# Cross-language interop happens at the CSS spec
# level - all three lanes parse the same W3C CSS
# specifications, so the same .css file produces
# structurally identical ASTs across all three.
# Output formatting + minification differ per lane.
# ============================================================================

_obelisk() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(-i --input)'{-i,--input}'[file containing URLs to archive]:file:_files' \
        '(-o --output)'{-o,--output}'[output file or directory (- = stdout)]:path:_files' \
        '(-c --load-cookies)'{-c,--load-cookies}'[Netscape-format cookie file]:file:_files' \
        '(-u --user-agent)'{-u,--user-agent}'[custom User-Agent string]:ua:' \
        '(-z --gzip)'{-z,--gzip}'[gzip-compress archival result]' \
        '(-q --quiet)'{-q,--quiet}'[disable all logging]' \
        '--verbose[verbose logging]' \
        '--no-js[strip JavaScript]' \
        '--no-css[strip CSS styling]' \
        '--no-embeds[strip embedded elements]' \
        '--no-medias[strip media elements]' \
        '(-r --retries)'{-r,--retries}'[max retries per request (default 3)]:N:' \
        '(-t --timeout)'{-t,--timeout}'[per-request timeout in seconds (default 60)]:secs:' \
        '--insecure[skip TLS certificate verification]' \
        '--max-concurrent-download[concurrent download cap (default 10)]:N:' \
        '--skip-resource-url-error[continue on resource fetch errors]' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '*:URL:'
}

_obelisk "$@"
